    "For each sample x, f (x) computes its probability estimation p(k|x) for each class k ∈ {1, • • •, K}, and K k=1 p(k|x) = 1.",
    "Throughout this paper, we refer to f (•) itself as the classifier.",
    "Training a classifier f (•) is to find an optimal classifier f * (•) that minimizes the empirical risk:N n=1 L(f (x n), y n), in which L: C×Y → R +is a loss function, and L(f (x), k) is the loss of f (x) with respect to label k.When label noise exists, the model can only access a corrupted dataset S η = {(x n, ŷn)} N n=1, where each sample is drawn i.i.d.",
    "from an unknown distribution Dη.",
    "In this context, minimizing the empirical risk N n=1 L(f (x n), ŷn) produces a classifier f * (•) optimized on the corrupted data."
